62. ‘He made him heir of his fortune by dying'. This should not be misunderstood, as if he had instituted him his heir on the day of his death.

63. ut ibat sorte like the Greek ὠς ἐτύγχανε πορευόμενος. But ut with the imperf. is not very common.-F or the perfect plfii comp. Varro de lingua lat. 111 104 (p. 232 Miiller) ε quidam ‘reprehendunt quodpluit et luit dicamus in praeterito et prae— senti tempore, cum analoqiae sui cuiusque temporis verba debeant discriminare. falluntur; nam eet ac putant aliter, quod in praeteritis u dicimus lonyum, plait lain in praesenti breve, plait tait. The fact is that there were two roots, plu· and plouv-‚ compare pluvius, Plu- viae and the verb perplovere quoted by Festus p. 250, 29. Hence the perfect plin· or plavi. The root plov- or plouv- appears also in plorare=ploverare. In

the same manner we have from nuo the perf. nni, comp. adunit used by Ennius ap. Priscian. x 12 p. 504 n. (In some editions we read pluverat.)
